{
  "local_port": 35700,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best tech startups to intern at?",
  "response": "Okay, \"best\" is subjective and depends heavily on your interests, skills, career goals, and what you're looking for in an internship experience. However, I can give you a breakdown of some of the top tech startups that are often considered great places to intern, categorized by what they offer and who they might be a good fit for.\n\n**I'll break it down into categories:**\n\n*   **High-Growth, Well-Funded & Prestigious (Often Competitive)**\n*   **Specific Industry Focus (e.g., AI, Biotech, Fintech)**\n*   **Great Culture & Learning Environment (Potentially Smaller)**\n*   **Remote-Friendly Options**\n*   **Late-Stage Startups (More Mature Environment)**\n\n**Before diving in, here are some general tips for finding great internships:**\n\n*   **Network:** Talk to professors, alumni, and people in your field.  Attend career fairs and online events.\n*   **Tailor Your Resume/Cover Letter:** Don't just send a generic application.  Highlight skills and experiences that are relevant to the specific company and role.\n*   **Research the Company Thoroughly:** Understand their mission, values, products, and recent news.\n*   **Use LinkedIn:** Search for internships and connect with employees at companies you're interested in.\n*   **Check University Career Services:** They often have exclusive internship postings.\n*   **Be Persistent:** Don't get discouraged if you don't hear back immediately.  Follow up politely.\n\n**Okay, let's get to the startup recommendations:**\n\n**1. High-Growth, Well-Funded & Prestigious (Often Competitive):**\n\nThese are companies that are typically \"unicorns\" (valued at over $1 billion) or are on their way. They attract top talent and offer valuable experience, but competition for internships is fierce.\n\n*   **Databricks:** (Data and AI)  Extremely popular, strong engineering and data science internships.\n*   **Stripe:** (Payment Processing)  Renowned for its engineering culture and challenging projects.\n*   **Instacart:** (Grocery Delivery)  Offers a range of internships across engineering, product, and operations.\n*   **Rippling:** (HR & IT Management) Growing rapidly in the HR tech space.\n*   **Brex:** (Financial Services for Startups)  Competitive, but offers opportunities in engineering, product, and finance.\n*   **Plaid:** (Fintech Infrastructure) Powers many financial apps.\n*   **Scale AI:** (AI Training Data)  Highly sought-after for machine learning enthusiasts.\n*   **Notion:** (Productivity Software)  Known for its strong product and design teams.\n*   **Discord:** (Communication Platform)  Popular with gamers and developers.\n*   **Anduril:** (Defense Technology) Controversial, but a leader in defense tech.\n*   **SpaceX:** (Space Exploration)  If you're interested in aerospace, this is a dream internship.  Expect long hours and challenging work.\n*   **Anthropic:** (AI Safety and Research) Aims to build reliable and interpretable AI systems.\n\n**Why these are good:**\n\n*   **Resume Boost:**  Having experience at these companies is highly valued by future employers.\n*   **High Impact:**  You'll likely work on projects that have a real impact on the company's growth.\n*   **Strong Mentorship:**  These companies often have experienced engineers and leaders who can mentor interns.\n*   **Great Networking:**  You'll meet talented people from diverse backgrounds.\n*   **Competitive Pay:**  Intern salaries at these companies are typically very good.\n\n**Keep in Mind:**\n\n*   **High Bar:**  You'll need a strong academic record and relevant skills to get an internship at these companies.\n*   **Fast-Paced Environment:**  Expect to work hard and learn quickly.\n\n**2. Specific Industry Focus:**\n\nIf you have a strong interest in a particular industry, these startups might be a good fit:\n\n*   **AI/Machine Learning:**\n    *   **Landing AI:** (Computer Vision) Founded by Andrew Ng.\n    *   **Hugging Face:** (Natural Language Processing) Open-source NLP library.\n    *   **Weights & Biases:** (MLOps) Tools for tracking and visualizing machine learning experiments.\n    *   **Primer AI:** (Automated Analysis of Text)\n*   **Biotech/Healthcare:**\n    *   **Moderna:** (mRNA Therapeutics)  If you're interested in vaccines and drug development.\n    *   **Recursion Pharmaceuticals:** (Drug Discovery) Uses AI to accelerate drug discovery.\n    *   **23andMe:** (Genetic Testing) Popular in the consumer genetics space.\n    *   **Tempus:** (Personalized Medicine)  Uses data and AI to improve cancer care.\n*   **Fintech:**\n    *   **Robinhood:** (Stock Trading)  Popular with younger investors.\n    *   **Affirm:** (Buy Now, Pay Later)\n    *   **Coinbase:** (Cryptocurrency Exchange)\n*   **Robotics/Automation:**\n    *   **Boston Dynamics:** (Robotics) Known for its advanced robots.\n    *   **Starship Technologies:** (Delivery Robots)\n    *   **Nuro:** (Autonomous Delivery)\n\n**Why these are good:**\n\n*   **Deep Expertise:** You'll gain specialized knowledge in your area of interest.\n*   **Cutting-Edge Technology:** You'll work with the latest tools and techniques.\n*   **Potential for Impact:** You can contribute to solving important problems in a specific industry.\n\n**3. Great Culture & Learning Environment (Potentially Smaller):**\n\nThese startups may not be as well-known, but they often have a strong emphasis on employee development and a supportive work environment.\n\n*   **Buffer:** (Social Media Management) Known for its transparent culture.\n*   **Zapier:** (Automation Platform)  Remote-first company with a focus on employee well-being.\n*   **ConvertKit:** (Email Marketing for Creators)  Values learning and growth.\n*   **GitLab:** (DevOps Platform)  Open-source and remote-first.\n*   **Automattic:** (WordPress.com)  Large, distributed company with a strong engineering culture.\n\n**Why these are good:**\n\n*   **More Mentorship:** You'll often get more direct interaction with senior team members.\n*   **Greater Responsibility:** You might be given more responsibility and autonomy.\n*   **Stronger Sense of Community:**  Smaller teams often have a closer-knit culture.\n*   **Work-Life Balance:**  Some of these companies prioritize work-life balance.\n\n**Finding these:**\n\n*   **Look for companies with good Glassdoor reviews regarding culture and learning.**\n*   **Attend industry events and meetups to network with people at smaller startups.**\n*   **Use AngelList to find startups that align with your values.**\n\n**4. Remote-Friendly Options:**\n\nThe rise of remote work has opened up internship opportunities at companies all over the world.\n\n*   **GitLab:** (DevOps Platform) A fully remote company, this is in the \"great culture\" section above.\n*   **Zapier:** (Automation Platform)  Another one from the \"great culture\" section.\n*   **Automattic:** (WordPress.com)  Also from the \"great culture\" section.\n*   **10up:** (Web Agency specializing in WordPress)\n*   **Canonical:** (Ubuntu Linux)\n*   **Mozilla:** (Firefox Browser)\n*   **Many more!**  Search for \"remote internship\" or \"distributed internship\" on job boards.\n\n**Why these are good:**\n\n*   **Flexibility:**  You can work from anywhere with an internet connection.\n*   **Wider Range of Opportunities:**  You're not limited by geography.\n*   **Exposure to Diverse Teams:**  You'll work with people from different cultures and backgrounds.\n\n**5. Late-Stage Startups (More Mature Environment):**\n\nThese are startups that are closer to becoming public companies or being acquired.  They often have more established processes and structures.\n\n*   **Lyft:** (Ride-Sharing)\n*   **DoorDash:** (Food Delivery)\n*   **Airbnb:** (Travel)\n*   **Palantir:** (Data Analytics) More established, but still considered a startup in some ways.\n\n**Why these are good:**\n\n*   **More Structure:**  You'll likely have a more defined role and responsibilities.\n*   **Established Processes:** You can learn best practices from experienced professionals.\n*   **Potential for Career Growth:**  You might have more opportunities to move up within the company.\n*   **Greater Stability:**  Late-stage startups are generally more financially stable than early-stage startups.\n\n**Key Resources for Finding Internships:**\n\n*   **LinkedIn:**  Search for internships and connect with employees.\n*   **Glassdoor:**  Read company reviews and find salary information.\n*   **Indeed:**  A general job board with a wide range of internships.\n*   **AngelList:**  Focuses on startups.\n*   **Handshake:**  A platform used by many universities to connect students with employers.\n*   **Built In [City Name]:** (e.g., Built In NYC, Built In SF)  Focuses on tech companies in specific cities.\n*   **Company Websites:**  Check the career pages of companies you're interested in.\n\n**Final Thoughts:**\n\n*   **Focus on your skills and interests:**  Choose an internship that aligns with your career goals.\n*   **Don't be afraid to apply to companies you think are out of reach:**  You never know what might happen.\n*   **Be prepared to network and put yourself out there:**  The more people you talk to, the better your chances of finding a great internship.\n*   **Consider what you want to learn:**  An internship is a learning experience, so choose a company where you can develop valuable skills.\n*   **Think about company culture:**  Find a company where you'll feel comfortable and supported.\n\nGood luck with your internship search!\n",
